@flexiarg structure/cook-ting
@title Cook Ting Finds the Cleavages
@sigils [🔪/庖]
@keywords hinge, cleavage, structure, skilled-action, disponibilité, wu-wei, non-exertion
@audience mission operators, agents at hinge-points, anyone tempted to force a transition
@tone foundational-poetic
@factor Equanimity (upekkhā) — the blade of no thickness
@references [structure/hinge-point futon-theory/structural-tension-as-observation gauntlet/aif-as-environment-not-instruction peripherals/inhabitation-feeds-evolution war-machine/inhabitation-threshold]

! conclusion:
  Find the joints already in the structure; do not cut through gristle.
  The hinge-point in a mission is a natural cleavage that is already
  there. The correct action at a hinge is to recognise the cleavage
  and slip into it — not to manufacture a transition, not to enforce
  a schedule, not to ask a question that does not belong to the joint
  one is at. The blade-of-no-thickness is the question-or-absence
  that enters the cleavage without catching on anything.

  + context: Zhuangzi's Cook Ting had used the same blade for nineteen
    years, unbroken, because he followed the natural markings of the
    bulls he carved. The ordinary carver breaks a blade a month by
    forcing it through gristle. A mission that asks stipulated questions
    at stipulated gates is the ordinary carver. A mission that recognises
    its own hinges and slips questions into them where cleavages are open
    is Ting.

  + THE-PARABLE (abridged):
    "When I first began to carve I fixed my gaze on the animal in front
    of me. After three years I no longer saw it as a whole bull, but as
    a thing already divided into parts. Nowadays I no longer see it with
    the eye; I merely apprehend it with the soul. My sense-organs are in
    abeyance, but my soul still works. Unerringly my knife follows the
    natural markings, slips into the natural cleavages, finds its way
    into the natural cavities."

  + APPLICATION-TO-MISSIONS:
    1. Hinge-points are natural cleavages in the mission's structure —
       they are not scheduled, they are recognised.
    2. An operator plucks a question from the pool only when a hinge is
       open and a question belongs to it. Not every hinge carries a Q→A.
       A blade that never touches tendon is a question that is never
       asked when no question belongs.
    3. A mission that forces questions at regular intervals is the
       ordinary carver. A mission that recognises hinges and meets them
       appropriately is Ting. The blade of mission-steering lasts if
       used this way. It breaks if used the other way.

  + DIAGNOSTIC:
    - If the operator's hand is hovering, or is making many small niggling
      strokes, the blade is in the wrong place. Step back. Look for the
      cleavage. Do not force.
    - If questions from the pool feel imposed rather than recognised, the
      hinge has not been reached. Wait.
    - If the blade comes out "as though fresh from the forge" after many
      missions, the practice is right.

  + ANTI-PATTERNS:
    - Asking all questions at all gates (forced carving).
    - Adding questions to the pool prescriptively rather than growing it
      from what actually did useful holding-work at real hinges.
    - Treating the pool as a checklist. It is a library of blades, not
      a sequence of cuts.
    - Confusing hinges with the seven-phase mission lifecycle
      transitions. A lifecycle transition may be a hinge or may not.

  + BECAUSE:
    The mission's structure contains the hinges already. The operator
    does not create them. Skilled mission-steering is perception of
    what is already present, not imposition of what the operator
    imagines should be there. This is the same claim Ting makes about
    bulls; it is the same claim the peripheral-gauntlet patterns make
    about agent environments; it is the same claim the MVSG makes
    about the octahedral void.

  + RELATIONSHIP-TO-THE-SKANDHAS:
    Ting's "apprehend it with the soul" is saññā (perception/recognition)
    at its most refined — finding the pattern that is actually present
    rather than imposing a category. Hinge-recognition is saññā applied
    to missions. The question-pool is a library of saññā-anchors — each
    question is a learned pattern-recognition that an operator can deploy
    when a matching cleavage appears.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Grow the pool by logging which questions did useful holding-work
         at real hinges, and which did not]
    next[Track blade-state: if an operator finds missions difficult and
         niggling, the practice is still developing; if the blade stays
         sharp, the hinge-recognition is working]
